  "text": "Again, we analyze S i for a fixed number i = 99 of unfoldings. Using the over-approximating semantics of [CITATION_1] , we get in which terms from ε 101 to ε 198 account for the over-approximation of non-linear computations, and do not correspond to inputs. A sequence of inputs leading to a bad-case scenario is thus not given directly by the sign of the ε 1 , . . . , ε 100 as in the linear case. Hence one cannot use the same technique as before, to be sure to reach the supremum of the range for S 99 . One can get a plausible worst-case scenario by choosing the E 0 , . . . , E 99 that maximize the sub affine form containing only these ǫ k , but one has no assurance that this might be even close to the real supremum of S 99 . But we will show that the under-approximating form allows us to choose at least part of the inputs.",
